{"id":"1807.00341","submitter":"Luca Rossi","authors":"Luca Rossi","title":"The Landis conjecture with sharp rate of decay","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.AP","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The so called Landis conjecture states that if a solution of the equation\n$$\\Delta u+V(x)u=0$$ in an exterior domain decays faster than $e^{-\\kappa|x|}$,\nfor some $\\kappa>\\sqrt{\\sup |V|}$, then it must be identically equal to $0$.\nThis property can be viewed as a unique continuation at infinity (UCI) for\nsolutions satisfying a suitable exponential decay. The Landis conjecture was\ndisproved by Meshkov in the case of complex-valued functions, but it remained\nopen in the real case. In the 2000s, several papers have addressed the issue of\nthe UCI for linear elliptic operators with real coefficients. The results that\nhave been obtained require some kind of sign condition, either on the solution\nor on the zero order coefficient of the equation. The Landis conjecture is\nstill open nowadays in its general form. In the present paper, we start with\nconsidering a general (real) elliptic operator in dimension $1$. We derive the\nUCI property with a rate of decay $\\kappa$ which is sharp when the coefficients\nof the operator are constant. In particular, we prove the Landis conjecture in\ndimension $1$, and we can actually reach the threshold value $\\kappa=\\sqrt{\\sup\n|V|}$. Next, we derive the UCI property -- and then the Landis conjecture --\nfor radial operators in arbitrary dimension. Finally, with a different\napproach, we prove the same result for positive supersolutions of general\nelliptic equations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 1 Jul 2018 15:16:22 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 14 Oct 2020 10:04:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-10-15"}
